Q1.1 Discussion [1]¶

Question at hand: Count the number of records/examples where the "Treatment_Response" feature is non-missing. Describe these examples in terms of the other features (Year from XXXX to YYYY, Gender = X etc.)¶

As seen in the above code snippet, the total number of records where "Treatment_Response" is non-missing comes to be 15. The values from this attribute are binary, and are either Success or Failure, representing treatment result. Now, regarding examples in terms of other features, let us list them:

  1. Class - All relevant records belong to the AML class, which corresponds to Acute Myelogenous Leukemia.
  2. BM_PB - Almost all records (14/15) belong to the BM (bone marrow) class, and only one to the PB (peripheral blood) class.
  3. TB_if_ALL - All records missing, as it corresponds to the ALL class.
  4. FAB_if_AML - All records present, ranging from M1 to M5 (severity), which are subtypes of AML.
  5. Year - All records missing, represents year of taking the sample.
  6. Gender - All records missing, represents patient gender.
  7. Source - All records set as CALGB, meaning all data has been retrieved from a single hospital.
  8. PS/pct_Blasts - All records present, treatment-related.
  9. D49950...U29175 - All records present, gene expression values for the respective genes, measured by an Affymetrix chip. All of the genes have been determined to be relevant.

As we can see, although all data has been retrieved from a single place, records relating to Gender and Year are missing; the reasons for it are unknown. Perhaps the hospital did not or could not store that patient data. However, other listed attributes are complete, and most of them are much more relevant to the problem at hand. The most important attributes seem to be of course treatment-related (PS/pct_Blasts) as well as gene readings.

Additionally, complete attribute description has been printed using pd.df.describe(include="all") functionality, but not much relevant numeric information can be really retrieved for most of the columns, therefore ignored.

[1] Genes-Leukemia dataset metdata: https://www.kdnuggets.com/data_mining_course/data/genes-leukemia-description.txt

Q1.2 (1 mark)¶

Explain why it is not correct to build predictive models for "Treatment_Response" using records where it is missing?

Q1.2 Answer¶

Discussion [1]¶

Building a predictive model requires data with known outcomes for given attributes to train on (supervised learning). Such models recognize patterns and relationships between variables to more accurately predict the outcome. Therefore, it is expected to provide the model with information that would allow it to map expected predictions to relevant attributes. A few reaons why predictive models are not suitable for predicting "Treatment_Response" using records where it is missing include:

  1. No truth to train on - inherently, the model needs to know the actual outcomes to learn relationships in data. To adjust its mappings/parameters, such models try to minimize the error between predicted and actual outcomes in order to improve accuracy. Without such information, the models simply have no reference points to learn from, rendering such records useless at best. The same of course can be said about evaluation of results; there is no way of doing that without ground truth.

  2. Misleading results - those missing records can easily guide the model into wrong predictions. For example, if the data is not missing at random and there are some underlying reasons why, we can train and bias the model on incorrect relationships, rendering it useless. Even if we try imputation, without great amount of research and expertise (for this case, in leukemia treatments), we can very easily introduce a lot of noise and/or bias, skewing our data.

  3. Violation of Supervised assumption - supervised learning is based on the idea that there are some attributes and ground truth to be mapped. Introducing incomplete cases, we immediately violate the basis of such methods, making them inappropriate for the task at hand.

Ultimately, predictive models require ground truth in order for successful training to take place. Utilizing records where our expected outcome is missing is simply violating inherent assumptions, and imputation can be extremely difficult and tricky for some cases.

References¶

[1] Hastie, T.; Tibshirani, R.; Friedman, J. (2009). "The Elements of Statistical Learning". Springer. ISBN 978-0-387-84857-0.

Q1.3 Discussion¶

Question at hand: Remove the features that are either all the same or have all missing values. Which sample fields should you keep?¶

We have removed the following attributes for given reasons:

  1. CLASS/Source - all entries for these features are the same, and therefore do not introduce any additional/differentiating anyformation that could help predictions.
  1. TB_if_ALL/Year/Gender - all entires for these attributes have the "?" value assigned to them, meaning they are missing and cannot provide any information.
  1. FAB_if_AML - although entries differ and could introduce relevant information, we remove it for simplicity.
  1. BM_PB - most entries (14/15) share the same value BM, and although one value differs PB, there is not enough diversity in the data for that attribute to be left. Of course, this attribute might be somewhat important for classification, but in the current state, it could lead to bias and (most likely) incorrect result that if BM_PB=PB then Treatment_Response=Success. One could argue that removing the whole row for sample s52 and then removing the attribute would also work in reducing/removing bias. However, this approach seems to lose much more information than what it gains in terms of performance. Therefore, we leave the sample and ignore the attribute.

We have kept the following attributes for given reasons:

  1. pct_Blasts/PS - attributes related to treatment, records differ between each other, therefore introduce relevant information about treatment result.
  2. Treatment_Response - as it is our target, we must of course keep it.
  3. D49950...U29175 - as previously stated; gene expression values for the respective gene, all of the genes have been determined to be relevant, therefore introduce relevant information about treatment result.

Fit a decision tree (DecisionTreeClassifier) using default settings to the data, now that it has been pre-processed.

As we have a small amount of data, if we want to more meaningfully assess the performance, we should use leave-one-out cross-validation. Report the accuracy across each fold, and the overall mean accuracy obtained.

Important: Please use random_state=42 where necessary to ensure reproducible results.

Q1.4 Answer¶

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import LeaveOneOut
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
import numpy as np

# Initalize the DTC, LOO-CV, accuracy per fold list, as well as x/y vals
dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
loo = LeaveOneOut()
res_acc = []
x_vals = tr_final_data.drop(columns=["Treatment_Response"])
y_vals = tr_final_data["Treatment_Response"]

# For each fold, fit the model and save accuracy
for train_idx, test_idx in loo.split(x_vals):
    x_train, x_test = x_vals.iloc[train_idx], x_vals.iloc[test_idx]
    y_train, y_test = y_vals.iloc[train_idx], y_vals.iloc[test_idx]
    dtc.fit(x_train, y_train)
    y_pred = dtc.predict(x_test)
    res_acc.append(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))

### REPORTING ACCURACY VALUES

# Print saved accuracies per fold
for i, acc in enumerate(res_acc, 1):
    print(f"Accuracy for fold {i}: {acc * 100:.2f}%")

# Calculate and print overall mean accuracy
mean_acc = np.mean(res_acc)
print(f"Mean Accuracy: {mean_acc * 100:.2f}%")

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn import tree
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Split data into given ratio 75:25 using sklearn built-in function
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x_vals, y_vals, test_size=0.25, random_state=3)

# Train the DTC on train split
base_dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=3)
base_dtc.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Print base accuracy before predictor removal
base_acc = base_dtc.score(x_test, y_test)
print(f"Base Accuracy (before top predictor removal): {base_acc * 100:.2f}%")

# Visualise the tree and find the most important predictor
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
tree.plot_tree(base_dtc, feature_names=x_vals.columns, class_names=["Fail", "Success"], filled=True)
plt.show()

# Sanity check, can also be seen from graph above
ftr_idx = base_dtc.feature_importances_.argmax()
ftr_name = x_vals.columns[ftr_idx]
print(f"Most important predictor name: {ftr_name}")

# Remove the predictor from train data
x_train_pruned = x_train.drop(columns=[ftr_name])
x_test_pruned = x_test.drop(columns=[ftr_name])

# Train a new DTC for train attributes 
pruned_dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=3)
pruned_dtc.fit(x_train_pruned, y_train)

# Print new accuracy
pruned_acc = pruned_dtc.score(x_test_pruned, y_test)
print(f"Pruned Accuracy (after top predictor removal): {pruned_acc * 100:.2f}%")

# Visualise the pruned tree for comparison
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
tree.plot_tree(pruned_dtc, feature_names=x_train_pruned.columns, class_names=["Fail", "Success"], filled=True)
plt.show()

# Calculating Sensitivity/Specificity for Q1.6

# Getting predictions
y_pred_base= base_dtc.predict(x_test)
y_pred_pruned = pruned_dtc.predict(x_test_pruned)

# Setting confusion matrices
# Format is [[TN, FP], [FN, TP]]
cm_base = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_base)
cm_pruned = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_pruned)

# Get base tree metrics
sensitivity_base = cm_base[1, 1] / (cm_base[1, 1] + cm_base[1, 0])
specificity_base = cm_base[0, 0] / (cm_base[0, 0] + cm_base[0, 1])

# Get pruned tree metrics
sensitivity_pruned = cm_pruned[1, 1] / (cm_pruned[1, 1] + cm_pruned[1, 0])
specificity_pruned = cm_pruned[0, 0] / (cm_pruned[0, 0] + cm_pruned[0, 1])

# Print calculated values
print(f"Base Tree - Sensitivity: {sensitivity_base:.2f}, Specificity: {specificity_base:.2f}")
print(f"Pruned Tree - Sensitivity: {sensitivity_pruned:.2f}, Specificity: {specificity_pruned:.2f}")

Q1.6 (2 marks)¶

Which tree do you think is more generalizable? You may want to more thoroughly compare the trees (readability, sensitivity/specificity, structure simplicity, etc.).

Q1.6 Answer¶

Discussion [1], [2], [3]¶

Model generalization is an important aspect of any data-driven design, and requires several factors to be evaluated. For this question, we will focus and discuss the following:

1.Complexity/Structure Simplicity¶

Starting with the base tree, we see that it uses fewer features in order to make a prediction (only 1 at root) and trees that make decision based on fewer attributes are seen as more robust due to having rely on broader data characteristics and focus on straighter patterns. This in turn makes them less prone to be influenced by possible fluctuations between individual features. Such trees rely on more reliable/primary characterstics that represent data, rather than splitting focus on multiple features.

The pruned tree, on the other hand, has grown in complexity. Becuase of that, it has become more susceptible to minor details in training data. An increase in nodes indicates having to utilize more features in order to make decision, and these often are less reliable/alligned with the ground truth. This sometimes even might indicate the model starting to consider noise in order to fit better, which in turn makes it less generalizable.

2. Readability¶

Simpler trees, or in general simpler models, are inherently much more readable than complex ones. With fewer nodes, it is much easier to follow the logic and understand each decision, and why it is happening. This, of course, makes possible trouble-shooting and refinement easier. It also makes the whole process much more transparent, making validation and/or explanation to outside people much more efficient.

More complex trees, in turn, make intepretation and following the process' logic harder and harder with each additional node. Such nodes can also introduce more confuision and more work needed when trying to explain and/or improve the model. This is especially the case when the features are not straightforward, such as genes.

3. Accuracy¶

A 75% accuracy for the base model indicates a relatively good performance, as it is capable of predicting 3 out of 4 unseen samples correctly. This outcome, compared with model's simple structure, suggest that the chosen top indicator U82759 captures significant information about the ground truth we are trying to predict, which of course guarantees somewhat high resultant accuracy.

With the pruned top predictor, we see an immediate drop of 25%. The resultant accuracy of 50% is equivalent of flipping a coin for each sample. This indicates that the model struggles to make correct decisions without the predictor present. Because of that, it tries compensating with other features, making it more prone to mistakes with other data.

4. Sensitivity/Specificity¶

Obtained results:

Base Tree - Sensitivity: 1.00, Specificity: 0.67 Pruned Tree - Sensitivity: 0.00, Specificity: 0.67

As we can see, the base tree correctly identifies all of the positive cases, and 67% of the negative cases. For the pruned tree, it fails to identify any of the positive cases, but manages to also identify 67% of the negative cases. This difference is crucial, especially in this context, where appropriate treatment assesment and application can save lives.

5. Confidence/Gini impurity¶

The base tree has a direct path from its base with relatively high Gini impurity to leaves with 0 impurity, which showcases a decisive split in its decision process and showcases a high confidence when deciding the ultimate treatment classification. Because the process is so straightforward, the model does not require any other features as back-up.

Although pruned tree's root impurity remains the same, the addition of another decision node before reaching 0 impurity indicates the newly utilized attributes do not offer the same level of confidence when making decisions. It also undermines the value of initial split, as it must be backed by further conditions. This of course introduces more potential error into the whole process.

Summary¶

In summary, while both trees aim to achieve the same goal, it is clear that the base tree is more likely to generalize better on new, unseen data. This is backed by its strenght in its simplicity and utilization of top predictor. The pruned tree tries to utilize secondary features to make its predictions, but these ultimately fall short. Not only is the tree more complex and harder to read, it also has worse accuracy and sensitivity. So, in terms of generalizability, the simpler (base) model can capture the main trend without having to try and overfit, while also maintaining a simple and easy to follow structure.

import numpy as np    
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification

from sklearn.dummy import DummyClassifier
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score, roc_curve
import seaborn as sns

def get_data():
    # Create data
    data, labels = make_classification(
        n_features=2, n_redundant=0, n_informative=2,
        random_state=1, n_clusters_per_class=1
    )
    # Set the RNG
    rng = np.random.RandomState(42)
    # Add some noise
    data += 2 * rng.uniform(size=data.shape)
    return data, labels

def plot_boundary(X, ax, clf):
    # Plotting decision regions
    x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 1, X[:, 0].max() + 1
    y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 1, X[:, 1].max() + 1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(
        np.arange(x_min, x_max, 0.1),
        np.arange(y_min, y_max, 0.1)
    )
    Z = clf.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])
    Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)
    ax.contourf(xx, yy, Z, alpha=0.4)
    return ax
    
def boundary_full(data, labels, model, name, **kwargs):
    # Create estimator/model/classifier
    clf = model(**kwargs)
    # Fit the classifier
    clf.fit(data, labels)

    # Create axis
    _, ax = plt.subplots()
    # Call the provided function
    ax = plot_boundary(data, ax, clf)
    # Now add the data (using scatter)
    # Ensure to colour the points according to the prediction
    ax.scatter(data[:,0], data[:,1], c=labels, s=20, edgecolor="k")
    # Format the graph...
    ax.set_title(f"{name} - Accuracy: {clf.score(data, labels)*100:.2f}%")

def evaluate_model(model, data, labels, name):
    # Fit given model
    model.fit(data, labels)

    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(data)

    # Generate and print a classification report
    print(f"Classification Report for {name}:\n {classification_report(labels, predictions, zero_division=0)}")

    # Get confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(labels, predictions)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix for {name}")
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues")
    plt.show()

    # Get AUC-ROC (when applicable; ZeroR will have AUC of 0.5)
    if name != "ZeroR":
        probs = model.predict_proba(data)[:, 1]
        auc = roc_auc_score(labels, probs)
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(labels, probs)
        plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
        plt.title(f"ROC Curve for {name} - AUC: {auc:.2f}")
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color="blue")
        plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle="--")
        plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
        plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
        plt.show()

Q2.1 Answer¶

Discussion [1], [2], [3], [4], [5], [6]¶

ZeroR brief¶

The "ZeroR" classifier, also known as the Zero Rule algorithm, is the simplest type of classifier. It does not really "learn" nor try to implement complex decision strategies. It disregards virtually all information and only uses the target class labels to make its predictions. It does that through simply predicting the most frequent class in the training dataset for all samples. It usually stands as a comparison point, or a baseline, for more sophisticated and complex algorithms/models. Therefore, introduction of any other features than target is useless. The working of this can be described as:

  1. Count the occurrences of each label in the training set data
  2. Find the most frequent class
  3. Predict most frequent class for all new data, regardless of their feature values

The decision boundary is virtually non-existent, as the class label assignment is done regardless of features.

KNN brief¶

K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN) is a type of an instance-based algorithm, where the model stores all instances of training data in a given feature space and classifies new entries based on a similarity measure. These measures are usually distance functions, such as Euclidean, Manhattan, and so on. A new entry is assigned to the class which has the most representatives within the nearest neighbours of that point (majority vote). The steps the algorithm follows are the following:

  1. Store all instances of the training data
  2. For a new incoming point, calculate the distance from the new point to all entries in the training data
  3. Find K instances in the training data that are the closest to new point
  4. Determine the most common label among those K nearest neighbours and assign that label to the new point

Decision boundaries are more nuanced, as they depend on the distribution of data within a given feature space. As the K value decreases, they can become more complex and irregular.

Decision tree brief¶

A Decision tree classifier utilizes several input features in order to predict the target variable. It does that through constructing a tree-like model of decisions, where each node acts like a test on a given attribute, and each branch a result of that test. The process starts at root node and later splits data on a given feature that results in the biggest information gain. This process is repeated over and over until the subtree contains only one class, or until it contains nodes with all equal values. The steps are as follows:

  1. Start at the root node
  2. Split the data based on the attribute that results in the largest information gain
  3. Repeat the process on data obtained from the split until all samples in the subsets belong to a single class, or until a given depth is reached

The decision boundaries for trees can be axis-aligned and piecewise linear, as they reflect the splitting process. As each split seperates the space into two regions, repeated recursively, these boundaries can be seen as straight seperation lines for each node in the space.

Differences between classifiers and resultant performance¶

ZeroR¶

We see, as predicted, a consistent prediction irrespective of the feature values. There is no seperation, all points have been clumped into a single classs. It was expected, as the method is not meant to differentiate points based on feature values, only on class frequency. As we set n_features=2, we expected accuracy of around 50%, and this is exactly what we achieved.

This is further solidified thanks to the confusion matrix and classification report, where we see that while the classifier correctly identifies instances of one class, it completely failed to recognize any instance of the second class. It can be stated, that due to the algorithm's nature, the accuracy and resultant performance indicator simply reflect the distribution of the most common class in the dataset. Resultantly, the ROC curve would simply be a diagonal line, meaning no discriminative power.

The most evident difference from other classifiers is the complete lack of any decision boundaries, meaning no attempts at segregation, which means that the classifier will perform poorly on any dataset that is not dominated by a single class, making it awkward to apply for any other reason than benchmarking.

KNN¶

For this classifier, we notice boundaries based on distance, which correspond to regions where each class is predicted. We also notice a more irregular split between boundaries, being resultant of localized patterns and classifications based on nearest neighbors. Given the algortihms nature, where classification is dependant on data distribution within the feature space, this is expected. However, these shapes could be even more irregular and fine-grained if we were to lower the K value.

With the accuracy of this approach being 96%, being much higher than the ZeroR benchmark, we see that the more complex split of the feature space is better at differentiating between nuances in the data. This can be further solidified thanks to the increase in matrix and classification report values. Although not perfect, the values represent the algorithm's ability to capture the trends and features much better; an AUC of 0.99 from the ROC curve indicates that the algorithm is has a high TP rate and a low FP rate, showcasing the ability to distinguish between classes effectively. This would be seen even better if small islands of points were present, however, this is not the case here.

The resultant 4 missjudged data points are due them being noisy and extremely hard to capture right without overfitting. As visible from the boundary condition and confusion matrix plots, these points are outliers and should most likely be discarded before fitting the model. However, they stand to showcase how the algorithm reacts to data that does not allign well with the general underlying trends, such as noise.

The most noticable differences are because of the point assignment based on majority vote of K-neighbours. The decision boundaries are more delicate and can adapt to fine-grained patterns in the data without overfitting much when applied correctly. However, too loose rules can make it overfit.

Decision tree¶

As predicted, for this approach, we see linear boundaries based on the tree's decision nodes, leading to rectangular sections of the feature space, where each class is dominantly predicted. This visualisation corresponds to the method's nature of creating rules based on given features to maximize the information gain. Given the specifics of how the algorithm handles its decision process, we see the regions/splits being made in a hierarchical manner, making the corresponding shapes better defined and linear.

Due to the decision tree's method of splitting the feature space based on attributes and rules, we see the resultant spaces containing only points of that class. With the accuracy being 100%, and resultant matrix and classification report values, we see that not a single point has been missjudged or wrongly assigned. This represent the algorithm's ability to capture all trends and smallest details within the data; an AUC of 1.00 further solidifies the lack of mistakes, emphasizing its distinction power between classes based on nuances.

However, having all of these points being correctly assigned does not have necessarily be a good indicator. As we see from the boundary plot, these contours look rather odd, having to split to cover all points, including added noise. Because of that we see that the model has created data-specific rules trying to cover all points in the data, making it less applicable and generalizable to unseen data. This performance is tied to the tree's depth; too shallow and the model will overfit, too deep and the model will overfit. The latter is the case here.

The most notable difference is of course the way boundaries are crated. Because of binary splits during decision process, the resultant shapes are more structured and result in clear rectangular splits in the space. Ultimately, of course depending on the tree's depth, this can make them very balanced at capturing trends.

Summary¶

ZeroR is just a baseline model with no real decision boundaries; its performance is uniform and dependant on data distribution. There is no insight given into the feature space.

KNN adapts to the feature space via distance-based methods and can display complex boundaries based on data. It is sensitive to local patterns, but can overfit when being made too flexible.

Decision Trees represent a hierachical approach, being represent by linear and structured decision boundaries regions. They can offer a balanced way of representing data, but this very much varies on the trees depth.

These differences underscore the trade-offs between simplicity and accuracy, overfitting and generalization capabilities, and between model interpretability and the ability to capture complex relationships in the data.

from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB

# Initialize arrays to store training time for each classifier
dtc_times = []
gnb_times = []

# Create test sizes, ranging from 1 to 10,000 in increments of 10
sizes = list(range(1, 10001, 10)) 

# Loop through sizes and save train time for each method
for size in sizes:
    data, labels = create_data(size)
    
    # Measure and save the time for DTC
    start = time()
    dtc = DecisionTreeClassifier()
    dtc.fit(data, labels)
    end = time()
    dtc_times.append(end - start)

    # Measure and save the time for GNB
    start = time()
    gnb = GaussianNB()
    gnb.fit(data, labels)
    end = time()
    gnb_times.append(end - start)

# Plot the resultant train times
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(sizes, dtc_times, label="DecisionTreeClassifier")
plt.plot(sizes, gnb_times, label="GaussianNB")
plt.xlabel("Data Size")
plt.ylabel("Training Time (s)")
plt.legend()
plt.title("Training Time vs. Data Size")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Q3.1 Discussion [1], [2], [3]¶

Based on the above plot representing train times for different dataset sizes, we can conclude the following:

  1. Training time and fluctuations - although both methods have relatively low training times even at larger datasizes (never breaching 0.05s), we can see that the Decision Tree Classifier increases somewhat linearly with the size, whereas the Gaussian Naive Bayes seems to stay stable and constant. Fluctuations in the training time are visible for both methods, however, the DTC's ones are much more pronounced and erratic, whereas GNB are much calmer.

  2. Stochasticity - the resultant variations and fluctuations can be further attributed to the inherent nature of both methods, especially for the DTC. This is the result of how the trees are built, which is especially pronounced when there is randomness in features splits. While traditional DTC is deterministic for a fixed dataset and set of hyperparameters, the randomness can occur from situations like: data splitting - feature split might be choosen randomly if two features provide the same information gain, random features subsets, or bootstrapping techniques. However, a basic DTC will generally produce the same tree when trained with the same hyperparameters and data unless there is a tie a feature split criterion. Although standard GNB is also deterministic, and will always compute the same class priors and feature likelihoods given a dataset, it can be influenced. These variations can cone in forms of initialization, handling zero probabilities, feature selection and data order. However, in general, for a traditional GNB, any stochasticity arises purely from specific extensions or variations of the algorithm, or preprocessing steps.

  3. Algorithm complexity and implementation - the training complexity of a DTC is typically O(n*m*log(m)), where n is the number of features and m is the number of samples. However, the tree is often pruned and doesnt grow to the fullest extent. Moreover, the actual applications often include other heuristics and optimization methods, such as using random feature subsets or limiting the tree's depth, decreasing the complexity. The GNB, under the assumption of normally distributed data, has a training complexity of O(n*m). It also utilizes statistical operations such as mean and variance for each class-feature combination. However, the inherent simplicity of underlying math operations translates into more efficient software implementations. Still, certain aspects, such as underflow for small probabilities, can sometimes affect the efficiency. These behaviour differences in both pure and modified implementations further explain the visible trends in the graph and resultant differences in training times between both methods when datasize becomes larger and larger.

Summary¶

While both methods have proven to be efficient in the given working environment, it has become apparent that DTC showcases more variability and increased training time with larger datasets. This is due to its algorithmic complexity and the somewhat stochastic nature of the mechanism behind decision tree building. On the other hand, GNB maintains consistent and linear performance, due to its simpler mathematical background and more deterministic nature.

Q3.2 (2 marks)¶

What do you think would happen if we continue increasing the number of instances? Which of the algorithms would be more suitable for a very large number of instances and why? Consider the algorithms complexity and how they scale.

Q3.2 Answer¶

As previously noticed, with the increased number of instances the expected training time for DTC would increase at a much more noticable rate than GNB. But in order to answer the question at hand, let us also focus on the following:

  1. Scalability and suitability for large datasets - GNB scales better with increased number of either instances or features due to its less demanding computational operations regarding statistics. Because of that, it is more suited to handle larger and more varied datasets, especially when the resources and latency are limiting factors.

  2. Algorithmic complexity - as previously stated, DTC has a training time complexity of O(n*m*log(m)), whereas GNB has O(n*m), where n is the number of features and m is the number of samples. Immediately, we see that DTC is much more sensitive to increase in data size or features, and while operations like pruning or limiting tree's depth can help, they do not fix the inherent method's complexity, rendering it expensive for very large datasets

  3. Possible trade-offs - of course, when talking about suitability, scalability and latency should not be the only factors. Other important factors might include performance, interpretability, or inherent nature of data. A method can be both fast and scalable, but might be unusuable in some cases.

In summary, if our primary goal is to minimize training time and ensure the scalability of our approach, GNB is the much more suitable choice. However, other factors should also be included in that comparison to ensure completely appropriate selection.

Q4.1 Answer¶

From the obtained graphs, we can notice the following:

  1. Stable memory consumption at lower data sizes: initially, there is a very stable memory usage up until approx. Data Size = 50 for small scale or Data Size = 33,000 for larger scale. This could be attributed to the overhead of initializing the model and data structures that have a constant size regardless of the data being processed until a certain point of complexity.

  2. Rapid increase in memory usage: as the size breaches a certain point, the memory consumption starts to rise rapidly. This is expected, as decision trees tend to use more memory with increased data due to the construction of the tree itself; larger datasets lead to deeper and/or more branched trees, which in turn require more memory to accomodate these changes in new structure.

  3. Step growth: the right part of the graph suggests that memory usage grows almost in a step-wise manner when increasing in data size. This would correspond to a relatively consistent increase in memory usage per given size block, followed by an increase due to tree shapes change. These blocks indicate thresholds, where the tree can no longer sustain data given its previous structure and has to adjust.

On both scales we see that there are apparent thresholds where memory consumption rises sharply. This behaviour indicates that decision trees can handle growing datasets efficiently until they reach certain complexities/threshold, at which they require structural changes to accomodate new data and trends, leading to higher memory needs.

However, the model showcases somewhat impressive memory efficiency, handling both small and notably large datasets without a direct proportionate, linear, or otherwise unsustainable increase in memory usage.

Given this behavior, we should expect potential sudden memory spikes, especially when approaching data size thresholds, for example as seen in above graphs.

In summary, DTC exhibits periods of memory efficiency followed by sharp memory usage spikes at specific size thresholds. These spikes are the result of the tree having to change its structure to accomodate new data and trends found within. Of course, it only need to do that periodically, as after a given structure modification, the tree can handle more data until a new threshold is reached. Then, the process of restructurization repeats, and so the memory usage increases again.
